ngland":"England","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stalworth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Stallard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stallard","meanings":["English: nickname denoting either a sturdy, well-built person, or someone who was brave and reliable, from Middle English <i>stalward</i>, <i>stalworth(i)</i> ‘stalwart’ (Old English <i>stælwierthe</i>, a compound of <i>stǣl</i> ‘place’ + <i>wierthe</i> ‘worthy’)."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Stalworth was born in 1482, in Kirton, Lincolnshire, England, her father, Thomas Stalworth, was 32 and her mother, Mrs. Stalworth, was 28. She had at least 5 sons and 1 daughter with Sir Albert Richard Perry Of Kirkton. She died in 1528, in England, at the age of 46, and was buried in Kirton in Lindsey, Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"1482–1528":"1482–1528","1480–1594":"1480–1594","1502–Female":"1502–Surnud","1504–1556":"1504–1556","1505–1594":"1505–1594","1506–1544":"1506–1544","1508–Male":"1508–Surnud","1515–1565":"15